# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The code is written to solve a problem related to a game of bowling. The function isWinner takes in two vectors, player1 and player2, that represent the scores of the two players in the game.

The fn lambda function calculates the total score for a given player's vector. It does so by iterating through each frame and adding up the scores. If the current frame is a strike or spare, it adds bonus points accordingly.

The isWinner function then calculates the score difference between player1 and player2 by calling the fn function for each player's vector. If player1's score is greater, it returns 1 to indicate that player1 wins. If player2's score is greater, it returns 2 to indicate that player2 wins. If both scores are equal, it returns 0 to indicate a tie.

Overall, the code is intuitive in its approach and easy to understand. It uses lambda functions to reduce code duplication and improve readability. The use of simple if-else statements to determine the winner based on score difference is straightforward and easy to follow.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
This code defines a function named isWinner that takes two vectors player1 and player2 representing the scores of two players in a game of bowling.

The function first defines a lambda function named fn that takes an integer vector as an argument. This lambda function iterates over each element of the vector and adds up the score for each frame. If the current frame is a strike (10 pins knocked down on the first ball) or a spare (10 pins knocked down in two balls), it adds extra points accordingly. The lambda function returns the total score for the given vector.

The isWinner function then calls the fn function with player1 and player2 vectors to calculate their respective scores. It then calculates the difference between the two scores and returns 1 if player1 wins, 2 if player2 wins, and 0 if it's a tie.

Overall, the code follows a simple approach to calculate the total scores for both players and determine the winner based on their score difference. The use of a lambda function makes the code more concise and reusable, allowing the fn function to be called multiple times with different vectors.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The fn lambda function iterates over each element of the vector and performs a constant amount of work for each element. Therefore, the time complexity of fn is O(n), where n is the length of the input vector.

The isWinner function calls fn twice and performs a constant amount of additional work to calculate the score difference and determine the winner. Therefore, the time complexity of isWinner is O(n), where n is the length of the input vectors.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The fn lambda function does not allocate any additional memory other than the input vector. Therefore, the space complexity of fn is O(1).

The isWinner function uses a constant amount of additional memory to store the scores and score difference. Therefore, the space complexity of isWinner is O(1).

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    // Define a function named isWinner that takes two integer vectors as arguments
int isWinner(vector<int>& player1, vector<int>& player2) {
    // Define a lambda function named fn that takes an integer vector as an argument
    auto fn = [&](vector<int>& p) {
        // Initialize a variable named ans to 0
        int ans = 0; 
        // Loop through each element of the vector
        for (int i = 0; i < p.size(); ++i) {
            // Add the current element to ans
            ans += p[i]; 
            // If the previous element is 10, add the current element to ans
            // If the element two positions back is 10, add the current element to ans
            if (i && p[i-1] == 10 || i >= 2 && p[i-2] == 10) ans += p[i]; 
        }
        // Return the value of ans
        return ans; 
    }; 

    // Calculate the score of player1 by calling the fn function with player1 vector
    int player1_score = fn(player1);
    // Calculate the score of player2 by calling the fn function with player2 vector
    int player2_score = fn(player2);

    // Calculate the difference between the two scores
    int score_diff = player1_score - player2_score; 
    // If player1's score is greater than player2's score, return 1 (player1 wins)
    if (score_diff > 0) return 1; 
    // If player2's score is greater than player1's score, return 2 (player2 wins)
    else if (score_diff < 0) return 2; 
    // If both scores are equal, return 0 (tie)
    return 0; 
}

};
```





