# Intuition & Approach
- use a simulation strategy
- at each strike, reset the player's strike weight
- decrement strike weight every round 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
// 2ms Beats 87.37%

class Solution {
    public int isWinner(int[] player1, int[] player2) {

        int n = player1.length;

        int[][] pins = new int[2][n];
        pins[0] = player1;
        pins[1] = player2;

        // strategy: simulation

        int[] scores = new int[2];
        int[] strikeWeight = new int[2];

        for (int round = 0; round < n; ++round) {
            for (int player = 0; player < 2; ++player) {

                // determine multiplier
                int multiplier = 1;
                if (strikeWeight[player] > 0) {
                    multiplier = 2;
                }

                // add score to running total
                scores[player] += pins[player][round] * multiplier;

                // adjust strike count as needed
                if (pins[player][round] == 10) {
                    strikeWeight[player] = 2;
                } else {
                    strikeWeight[player] = clamp(strikeWeight[player] - 1, 0, 2);
                }
            }
        }

        // determine winner
        if (scores[0] > scores[1]) {
            return 1;
        } else if (scores[1] > scores[0]) {
            return 2;
        } else {
            return 0;
        }

    }

    private int clamp(int val, int lower, int upper) {
        if (val < lower) {
            return lower;
        } else if (val > upper) {
            return upper;
        } else {
            return val;
        }
    }

}


```

