# Intuition

The problem requires comparing the total scores of two bowling players. The score is calculated by doubling the current turn's pins if 10 were hit in the previous two turns, or else simply adding the current pins. By calculating each player's total score, we can compare and determine the winner.

# Approach

We just have to iterate through the array and add the values to a variable.

Whenever we hit a 10 we set the strikeCounter to two and decrease it the following two rounds by one until it is zero. Now we can always check if stikeCounter is bigger than 0 and in that case add the value a second time to the total.

At the end we just compare the two numbers and return the correct result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n + m)$$

We iterate through the two input arrays exactly one time each.

One could argue that this is $$O(n)$$ instead, because the arrays are the same size.

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$

We are only creating integer variables which are always the same size, so the space taken by this algorithm is constant -> $$O(1)$$

# Code
```
function isWinner(playerOne: number[], playerTwo: number[]): number {
    let scorePlayerOne = getScore(playerOne);
    let scorePlayerTwo = getScore(playerTwo);

    if (scorePlayerOne > scorePlayerTwo) {
        return 1;
    }

    if (scorePlayerOne < scorePlayerTwo) {
        return 2;
    }

    return 0;
};

function getScore(pinsHit: number[]): number {
    let total = 0;

    for (let i = 0, strikeCounter = 0; i < pinsHit.length; i++) {
        total += pinsHit[i];

        if (strikeCounter > 0) {
            total += pinsHit[i];
            strikeCounter--;
        }

        if (pinsHit[i] === 10) {
            strikeCounter = 2;
        }
    }

    return total;
}
```

