# Approach 1: vector (186ms)

Several solutions are using an ```std::unordered_map``` for building an index, which is a waste as we know that the elements in ```mat``` are within $$[1, n * m]$$, hence we can just directly index into a ```std::vector```.

```cpp
    static int firstCompleteIndex(const vector<int>& arr, const vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        const int rows = size(mat);
        const int cols = size(mat[0]);

        // build index for |mat|.
        vector<pair<int,int>> index(rows * cols + 1);
        for (int r = 0; r < rows; ++r)
            for (int c = 0; c < cols; ++c)
                index[mat[r][c]] = make_pair(r, c);

        // process |arr|.
        vector<int> rc(rows);
        vector<int> cc(cols);
        for (int i = 0; i < size(arr); ++i) {
            const auto [r, c] = index[arr[i]];
            if (++rc[r] == cols) return i;
            if (++cc[c] == rows) return i;
        }
        // unreachable.
        assert(false);
        return -1;
    }
```

**Complexity Analysis**
Let $$n$$ and $$m$$ be the dimension of ```mat``` and $$n * m$$ the size of ```arr``` then the 
  * Time complexity is $$O(n * m)$$ as we need to scan ```mat``` and ```arr``` and the
  * Space complexity is $$O(n * m)$$ for the index we build.


# Approach 2: dynamic array on stack (167ms, 100%?)
As pointed out @Ajna2, why bother with a vector when an array might be even cheaper. The code is kinda interesting that clang generates for multiple dynamic arrays on the stack: https://godbolt.org/z/h1975ojhj Instead of on the heap the temporary working memory is created on the stack. There is still an indirection happening though.

```cpp
    static int firstCompleteIndex(const vector<int>& arr, const vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        const int rows = size(mat);
        const int cols = size(mat[0]);

        // build index for |mat|.
        pair<int,int> index[rows * cols + 1];
        for (int r = 0; r < rows; ++r)
            for (int c = 0; c < cols; ++c)
                index[mat[r][c]] = make_pair(r, c);

        // process |arr|.   
        int rc[rows];
        fill(rc, rc + rows, 0);
        int cc[cols];
        fill(cc, cc + cols, 0);
        for (int i = 0; i < size(arr); ++i) {
            const auto [r, c] = index[arr[i]];
            if (++rc[r] == cols) return i;
            if (++cc[c] == rows) return i;
        }
        // unreachable.
        assert(false);
        return -1;
    }
```

