# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
To avoid repeatedly traversing the matrix, we can optimize the process by first traversing the matrix once and recording the position of each number in an unordered map. 

Then, we can traverse the array and for each index, we can look up the position of the corresponding number in the map. By subtracting 1 from the corresponding row and column in the matrix, we can keep track of which rows and columns have already been used. For example, if the number 3 is at mat[r][c], we would do rows[r]-- and cols[c]--. This is because we want to update the rows and columns to indicate that a column has been used in the "row r". 

Initially, each "row r" will have m columns available, but once rows[r] reaches 0, it means that the row has been occupied. We can then find the index to return, which is the same process we use for the columns.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Map + Count
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n*m)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n*m)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int firstCompleteIndex(vector<int>& arr, vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        int R = mat.size();
        int C = mat[0].size();

        vector<int> rows(R, C);
        vector<int> cols(C, R);
        unordered_map<int, pair<int,int>> Map;

        for(int i=0; i<R; i++){
            for(int j=0; j<C; j++){
                Map[mat[i][j]] = {i,j};
            }
        }


        for(int i=0; i<arr.size(); i++){
            auto [r,c] = Map[arr[i]]; 

            rows[r]--;
            cols[c]--;
            if(rows[r]==0 || cols[c]==0){
                return i;
            }
        }

        return -1;


    }
};
```

