# Intuition
Since all values in `arr` are unique, just keep count of how many remain in each row/column and return once any are empty

# Approach
We need to work backwards, since we want to be able to compute the validation (the actual computation) of first complete index quickly, spend time storing information that will speed that up.
## Passes
1) Pass through the whole matrix keeping track of where each value is. $O(MN)$
> since `mat` and `arr` are essentially permutations of $1-M*N$ where $M$ is the amount of rows and $N$ is the amount of columns, just keep the coordinates in 2 vectors of length $M*N+1$

2) Pass through `arr`, decrementing row and col at `arr[i]`'s coordinates then check if either are 0, then return or continue. $O(MN)$
### Primitive Variables:
- m: Rows of mat, save on function overhead per access
- n: Columns of mat, save of function overhead per access
### Vectors:
- coordsx: X coordinate of any given number
- coordsy: Y coordinate of any given number
- row: keeps track of how many cells are left in each row
- col: keeps track of how many cells are left in each column

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$O(MN)$ - Always needs to traverse mat w/ 2 operations per iteration step, does up to 2 checks and operations per iteration step of the validation

- Space complexity:
$O(MN)$ - needs 2 $M*N$ vectors/arrays for coordinates, needs 1 $M$ and 1 $N$ vector/array for validation

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int firstCompleteIndex(vector<int>& arr, vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        int m=mat.size(),n=mat[0].size();
        vector<int> coordsx(m*n+1),coordsy(m*n+1),row(m,n),col(n,m);
        for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){//store coordinates for later
                coordsx[mat[i][j]]=i;
                coordsy[mat[i][j]]=j;
            }
        }
        for(int i=0;i<m*n;i++){
            if(!--row[coordsx[arr[i]]]||!--col[coordsy[arr[i]]]){//decrement and check
                return i;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

