# Intuition
An unordered map with three elements each can be used to tackle the problem here.

# Approach
At first, an unordered map is declared having values *int*, and *pair* of *ints*. Here, the first *int* represents the value of an element in the matrix and the *pair* represents the address of the element in the matrix.

Along with that, two arrays of sizes *m* and *n* are created to store the number of elements painted in each row and column of the matrix.

The unordered map is initialised with the address of all the elements in the matrix using the *for* loop.

After that, the given array is traversed one by one, and corresponding to the address of the element in the unordered map, the values in *rows* and *columns* are incremented, marking the fact that one more element in that row/column has been painted.

If the number of rows or columns painted at any point matches the total number of rows/columns, the index of array at which this is achieved is simply returned.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
Since there are two *for* loops corresponding to the rows *m* and columns *n* of the matrix intertwined, the time complexity for this solution is **O(mn)**.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int firstCompleteIndex(vector<int>& arr, vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
    int i=mat.size(), j=mat[0].size(), k=arr.size();
    vector<int> rows(i);
    vector<int> columns(j); 
    unordered_map<int,pair<int,int>> map;

    for(int n=0;n<i;n++)
        for(int p=0;p<j;p++)
        {
            map[mat[n][p]].first=n;
            map[mat[n][p]].second=p;

        }

    for(int n=0;n<k;n++)
    {
        int x=arr[n];
        rows[map[x].first]++;
        columns[map[x].second]++;

        if(rows[map[x].first]==j || columns[map[x].second]==i)
            return n;
    }

    return 0;    
    }
};
```

