# Approach
1. A brute force attempt would mean you traverse arr, find element i in matrix O (n*m), color it then check if whole row or column is painted O (n+m).
2. You can optimize it by knowing WHERE exactly where each element is in the matrix.
    - Declare an int[n*m + 1] and store the prefixed order of each element:
    The last element in a n*m matrix would be mapped against the position n*m in the position array.
    EG: mat [[4,3],[1,2]] => int[] pos of size 5
    - 4 will be mapped as pos 0: pos[4] = 0;
    - 3 -> pos 1:  pos[3] = 1
    - 1 -> pos 2: pos[1] = 2
    - 2 -> pos 3: pos[2] = 3
3. This way, if we want to color element 1, we look at pos[1] = 2.
    - 2 / 2 = 1 => row 1 (i) - see point #5 & 6
    - 2 % 2 = 0 => col 0. (j) - see point #5 & 6
4. Furthermore, we don't really need to "paint" the matrix and traverse whole row/col and count the number of painted cells. We can keep track of how many painted cells are in each row/ column
5. Declare an int[mat.length] coloredRows and int[mat[0].length] coloredColumns.
6. Using the info from #3, increment coloredRows[1]++ and coloredColumns[0]++.
    If coloredRows[i] == numberOfColumns (all columns are painted on that row) OR coloredColumns[j] == numberOfRows (all rows are colored for that column) return index of arr. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(n*m + a)$$ a - size of arr
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(n*m + n + m)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
