# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
As every array value will be unique and exist in `mat` matrix, we can use **Counter** arrray(rows, cols) to count the **value positions**. And if we reach: 
- rows `count size == (matrix column).size` (C variable) OR
- cols `count size == (matrix rows).size` (R variable)

Return the arr `ith` index

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- **int[] rows = new int[R];** - Count of arr item position in rows
- **int[] cols = new int[C];** - Count of arr item position in columns
- **(int r, int c)[] positions = new (int r, int c)[R * C + 1];** - Store the value position as **Value tuple** `(int r, int c)`


# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(R * C )$$, where R, C = total Rows and Columns size
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(R * C)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public int FirstCompleteIndex(int[] arr, int[][] mat) {
        int R = mat.Length;
        int C = mat[0].Length;

        int[] rows = new int[R];
        int[] cols = new int[C];
        (int r, int c)[] positions = new (int r, int c)[R * C + 1];

        for (int i = 0; i < R; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < C; j++) {
                positions[mat[i][j]] = (i, j);
            }
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < arr.Length; i++) {
            (int r, int c) = positions[arr[i]];
            rows[r]++;
            cols[c]++;

            if (rows[r] == C || cols[c] == R) {
                return i;
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
}

```

