# Intuition
Since the matrix contains all integers in the range from `1` to `m * n` the values are unique in each cell we just need to keep track of the number of remaining cells in each row and in each column 

# Approach
- keep track of the location of each integer in a map for constant lookups 
- loop over the arr and reduce the corresponding row and column by 1 then check if either is `0` then return the integer 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: `O(m * n)`

- Space complexity: `O(m * n)`


# Code
```
/**
 * @param {number[]} arr
 * @param {number[][]} mat
 * @return {number}
 */
var firstCompleteIndex = function (arr, mat) {
    const locations = {};
    const M = mat.length
    const N = mat[0].length
    const cols = new Array(N).fill(M);
    const rows = new Array(M).fill(N);
    for (let i = 0; i < M; i++) {
        for (let j = 0; j < N; j++) {
            locations[mat[i][j]] = [i, j]
        }
    }
    for (let x = 0; x < arr.length; x++) {
        const [i, j] = locations[arr[x]];
        rows[i]--;
        cols[j]--;
        if (!rows[i] || !cols[j])
            return x;
    }
    return -1
};
```

