# Approach
Dynamic Programming where the minimum cost from the ending position of each special road is recorded. Initially the "minimum cost", or the `dp` array, stores the cost from the ending position to the target normally. Then I loop through the whole thing trying to make optimizations going through the specialRoads. After `specialRoads.length` loops, it should have had the chance, if necessary, to go through every possible combination of specialRoads. Thus now we have the minimum cost. 

However, it looks like everyone else is using Dijkstra's Algorithm, so I am not positive that this code does find the minimum cost every single time (although it does pass every test case).

Note I am not asking if this is the most optimized algorithm, because it definitely isn't. I am just asking if it works at all.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^3)$$

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$

where $n=\text{specialRoads.length}$.


