# Intuition
Trying to use the simplicity of distance formula failed miserably.
Trying to build a dynamic on cost wasn't of good progress as well.

# Approach
Vector `specialRoads` consists of starting point (`[0]`, `[1]`), finish point (`[2]`, `[3]`) and cost (`[4]`). Let's add `[5]` - the cheapest way to reach finish point of a road. Initially filled with the price to reach start plus price of a road usage.

This `[5]` will be relaxed (updated with a tightened approximation) `n-1` times. More is redundant. How? We take road `r` (to be relaxed) and for every road `R` we take price to reach finish point of `R`  plus price to move to the start of `r` plus price of road `r` usage. That's it. 

Leaving a comment is welcomed. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^3)$$. Implementations with another $$log(n)$$ are not gonna pass

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$. The only liniar data we introduce is fifth coordinate of `specialRoads`.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumCost(vector<int>& start, vector<int>& target, vector<vector<int>>& specialRoads) {
        for(auto& r : specialRoads)
            r.push_back(r[0]-start[0] + r[1]-start[1] + r[4]);
        for(int n{(int)specialRoads.size()}; --n;)
            for(auto& r : specialRoads)
                for(auto& R : specialRoads)
                    r[5] = min(r[5], R[5]+abs(R[2]-r[0])+abs(R[3]-r[1])+r[4]);
        int mn{target[0]-start[0] + target[1]-start[1]};
        for(auto& r: specialRoads)
            mn = min(mn, r[5] + target[0]-r[2] + target[1]-r[3]);
        return mn;
    }
};
```

